6 The Hebrew Law pormittod the relative of the person slain to kill the slayer, anywhere without the places of refuge: and the Hebrew commentators rightly note, that retaliation for a person slain might be executed by porsonal force3 but for the person himself, for example for a wound, no otherwise than before a judge ; because moderatiori is more difficule when the pain comes nearer ourselves. That a like mode of avonging murder by the hands of a private person prevailed among the Greeks of old, appears in Homer. But the examples of this are most frequent among those who have not a proper judge. Just wars, says Augustino, arc commonly defined to be
